<p>Hello Impperatrix! let's take a look :)</p>
<p><strong>SAND</strong></p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p><br />
<strong>The concept:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Elevator Pitch: A woman-like automaton that also can transform into a sword and fights using ballet moves. It always has a host/owner. The host experiences memories and has skills of the anterior hosts. The SCP's main action is protecting its current host.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Overall, theres quite a few elements here, and not all of them really feel linked with each other? I'm unsure on why it can transform into a sword, why it fights specifically with ballet moves, why it needs a host and why its main motive is to protect the owner.</p>
<p>As it stands these aspects feel sort of meaningless, as the skip doesn't really seem to have a purpose for most of them, nor does it really have a reason for protecting its hosts.-why is it so set on that?</p>
<p>That said, I quite like the idea that the skip passes down memories from previous owners. However, this aspect isn't really explored or focused on much in the narrative (at least not from what I can see). Which as a result makes the effect (and the skip to an extent) feel a bit flat.- does the skip pass down memories from other hosts kept in containment?</p>
<p><strong>The narrative:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Central Narrative: The narrative is more centred on the hosts, the &quot;SCP-XXXX-A&quot;. There will be three hosts. As the story progresses, the Foundation tries to contain the SCP as experiments with its owners. The owners start presenting some dangerous behaviors, the Foundation has to protect them more and more from themselves and from the SCP influence. Every owner iteration changes the article, including some description and containing methods.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Overall, there isn't really an arc here? while I like the approach taken conflict wise, there isn't really much explaining or expanding on where and how the skip was found, what is actually tested or why and how the characters keep getting experimented on (considering the narrative seems to imply the skip escapes multiple times?) and how the narrative ends.-whats the payoff here? how will the ending make me as the reader feel?</p>
<p>Along with this, I'm finding it a bit hard to get invested in the characters, as they don't really get established much. What will makes me as the reader care about them? what makes them interesting? how do they initially become a host?- what ends up happening to them?</p>
<p><strong>Hook:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>Hook/Attention-Grabber: Most of the time, the hosts actions are more connected to the Foundation's experiments and protocols than the SCP itself:</p>
<p>The first host uses a deprivation tank to revive ancient owners' memories, thus developing PTSD.<br />
The second host used to test the SCP's protection abilities, becoming paranoical and/or even homicidal.<br />
The last owner is treated as an object, being constantly protected and losing his free will.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This makes the Foundation look kind of cruel. As they don't seem to have much of a reason to be treating the skip and its hosts so harshly, what are they gaining from this? why is it more important to them than the skips wellbeing?</p>
<p><strong>Red or green?</strong><br />
Due to my afore mentioned concerns, no-greenlight.</p>
<p>If you would like me review this (or any concept) further, then please feel free to send me a PM or ask via IRC. Response times generally range from 2-12 hours over PMs. If your looking for additional critiques/perspectives in general, then I would highly recommend contacting the butterfly squad :)</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>Cheers,</p>
<p>RED</p>

