<p>Thank you so much for your help! I'll edit the first post with ideas that I had after and before your critics to improve the idea. I have an eight-paged document with ideas for this one, but I've tried to summary everything as I was nervous with the 400 words limit. I'll list above what will be revised.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;The&nbsp;Concept</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>I've listed everything and will answer your concerns one by one:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Protection Directive:</strong> This sword was created to be an &quot;Ultimate Weapon&quot; for an &quot;Ultimate Warrior&quot;. The protection it gives is based on the question &quot;can my owner defend itself from this attack&quot;? If the answer is &quot;No&quot;, it will transform into the automaton to defend it. If it is &quot;Yes&quot;, then it will continue as a sword. The system isn't perfect as it can't protect the host from anything non-humanoid (birds, plants, fungi, etc). It is closely connected with the memory keeping, as both the SCP and the owner have to be powerful combatants (see Memory Keeping above).</li>
<li><strong>Transformation:</strong> the sword is its &quot;dormant&quot; form and the automaton is its &quot;activated&quot; form. It will keep sword form till the &quot;protection directive&quot; is activated. As I forgot to mention, the automaton attacks are always slashing or piercing as a sword, even its punches or kicks. It comes from its references, but has a meaning.</li>
<li><strong>Ballet Dancing:</strong> That's my fault as I've forgot to mention previous owners. One of its owners was a soviet ballerina that fought in the Russian Civil War. As the ballet is based on perfection (one of the SCP keywords), it blended the dance with its fighting style. It is also a thing that comes from the SCP references.</li>
<li><strong>Memory Keeping:</strong> The SCP memory keeping is based on maintaining everything that can be used on warfare, mainly languages, martial arts, weapon mastery and other skills. It keeped full memory of its favorite masters (favorite almost meaning &quot;most sanguinary&quot;), including life and murdering scenes. This will be important to the next topic.</li>
<li><strong>Host Changing:</strong> The only way known to become a host is killing the previous one. If it dies of anything that is not murder, the SCP becomes a violent guard of its previous owner remains. Anyway, non-violent deaths are difficult to achieve, as the host is especially skilled for surviving.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Narrative&nbsp;and&nbsp;Hook</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>As both are very close, I'll write about them together, talking about the three hosts.</p>
<ol>
<li>The first gets the SCP control by accident, as it was an agent from a task force sent to control and retrieve the SCP. By them we first get the SCP idea. Because of its unknown intrusive memories, it gets an mnestics treatment as researchers think this will uncover the SCP's powers and history, but the host ends up having PTSD as it lives through the atrocities the previous host had made, killing another agent during one of its hyperarousal episodes. Without escape, the Foundation choses a new host.</li>
<li>The second one is used to test the SCP protection skills, as they continue unexplained. The researchers discover that it only replies to aggressions where the host is off guard. As the host accepts, they begin a series of tests based on surprise non-lethal ambushes. With the SCP psychic interference, the hosts start presenting paranoid and atypical behavior. As they start getting homicidal, a third host is chosen.</li>
<li>The third is less obvious. It gets special treatment as no one wants another murderous SCP host. They even get a Special Task Force just to protect them from dangers. It's implicit that the third host is treated more as an SCP subject than a human, as even with psychological, therapeutic and psychiatric treatments, the STF commander has the orders to kill them if they get out of control.</li>
</ol>
<p>I'll try to keep with the &quot;Cold, not Cruel&quot; and &quot;Flawed, not Fools&quot; all the time. I need more critics about it.</p>
