<p>Got a PM about this, took a look.</p>
<p>I'll be honest, this seems like a mishmash of unrelated elements picked because they kind of sound cool rather than because they work together to tell a coherent story. The inclusion of ballet, for example, seems extremely forced since not only do professional ballerinas injure themselves all the time for their art, ballet is (at least classically, if I recall correctly) meant to be performed to music, with pre-determined choreography. It would be a lot more work to try and adapt ballet to combat than, say, having someone train in self-defense techniques that are easier to learn if one has the flexibility of a principal dancer. (This admittedly reminds me of Pearl from Steven Universe.)</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>There's also the issue that the automaton's existence doesn't really make sense. If it wants to become a &quot;perfect weapon&quot;, why does it bother with incorporating ballet into its fighting skillset? If it's looking for a &quot;perfect warrior&quot;, why is it obligated to protect hosts who aren't guaranteed to be warriors at all?</p>
<p>I start losing interest immediately at:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>They are an common field agent that was in the wrong place at the wrong time. This host will discover SCP “memory flash drive&quot; powers and turned into the subject of an mnestic experiment to discover the SCP memories.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This sounds like a generic anime protagonist or the like: they start off as &quot;common&quot; but just happen to encounter an event that gives them a spontaneous superpower that conveniently makes the rest of the story possible. I find myself extremely skeptical that this agent not only happens to defeat the automaton, they also conveniently obtain powers for revealing extra information spoonfed-exposition-style. It feels contrived and doesn't make for a good story because it feels too convenient. Even the emotional element with the memory feels clumsily manipulative&#8212;having the amnestics not work because &quot;the automaton just does what it does&quot; is rather unsatisfying as a story point.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<blockquote>
<p>if you think the SCP is weak for being focused on its &quot;owner''.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I feel like the issue is more that this just feels like a rehash of Neon Genesis Evangelion, except the pilot's backstory is much blander and the associated automaton makes a lot less sense in-universe. If you really want to try to make this work, I feel like you're going to have to better develop the automaton first, since right now it seems to exist solely to facilitate this specific sob story about some random powered-up field agent. The audience isn't likely to take this seriously until you make the core anomaly more unique and narrative-driven rather than just a conglomerate of disparate aesthetics. Why does the automaton exist the way it does? How can you make that more meaningful to the average reader, who is very much a normal human with no powers and no resistance to amnestics?</p>

							</div>

								
					
