																		Re: Sword Ballerina (Seeking Greenlight)
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1404533&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610180966" alt="Zyn" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1404533)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/zyn" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1404533); return false;" >Zyn</a></span> <span class="odate time_1610178751 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">09 Jan 2021 07:52</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4865761">
									

<blockquote>
<p>The ballet dancing as a fighting style is something that only the automaton does</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I know. It doesn't make sense for the automaton to do it. It's overly flowery and kind of useless in combat&#8212;there's no need for flourishes or taking the time to do elegant poses in a street brawl. Or does this thing only get into fights if they're long, drawn out movie-style shows of acrobatics?</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>I'm really confused as to how I can improve this and I accept some help. If it really has to be deleted, I'll be sad, I admit, but I want to make this work.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Again, you need to figure out what the reason for the automaton to exist is. If it's just trying to be a &quot;perfect warrior&quot;, then you'd need to remove the gratuitous ballet stuff. It wouldn't make sense to sacrifice viability of technique for aesthetic&#8212;all of the examples you've mentioned are fictional animated characters, who don't need to be believable in terms of real-life maneuvering. If the automaton is trying to better itself through study of the arts, it makes more sense to keep that in.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>the are almost guaranteed to be warriors as the directive for the SCP to change its host is killing the previous host</p>
</blockquote>
<p>It doesn't take a warrior to kill someone.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>or (if the host is already dead) defeating the SCP in battle</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Again, all sorts of underhanded ways this very simple requirement can be exploited. Unless you've got some additional requirements to slap on that require &quot;honorable combat&quot; or the like, which just feels even more cliche and contrived.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>About the mnestics/amnestics, the SCP is somehow a &quot;backup file&quot;.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>My question is <em>why</em>. You've already got a lot of kind of random details, abilities, and restrictions that don't really match for the automaton; why does it need to be a backup file too?</p>
<p>Right now the automaton and the field agent seem like two characters from different stories, and all the accompanying details just overcomplicate the narrative; I say pick one to focus on and remove most of the minutiae from the other.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<blockquote>
<p>it is discovering the SCP rules, how it works and why it works this way. It seems simple, but there is this conundrum about exposing too much or too little of the SCP.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>When discussing concept, you always want to answer the reviewer's questions, even if it means &quot;exposing&quot; material. You do not help yourself at all by intentionally keeping things secret from the reviewer; reviewers will not automatically assume that what they don't know about the piece is automatically good.</p>
<p>If you don't have anything planned for why this automaton exists the way it does, just say that. If you do have a backstory for why it acts this way, <em>tell the reviewers</em> so we can let you know if we think it's a good story or not.</p>

							</div>

								
